REPORT 8 — Australian APRA CPS 234 Vendor Readiness Assessment
Title: Third‑Party Information Security Readiness Assessment for Cloud Analytics Vendor — APRA CPS 234 Compliance Review
Region: Asia-Pacific (Australia)
Industry: Financial Services (Banking)
Author: Ssambra — Identity Auditor & Threat Sentinel

1. Executive Summary
An Australian mid‑tier bank engaged a cloud analytics vendor to support fraud‑detection modeling. During onboarding, the vendor failed to meet several APRA CPS 234 requirements, including:

No evidence of control effectiveness testing

Weak incident response capability

Incomplete access control governance

Insufficient security capability for a regulated environment

No formal third‑party dependency management

Breach notification timelines misaligned with APRA requirements

This assessment evaluates the vendor’s readiness to support an APRA‑regulated entity and identifies gaps that must be remediated before onboarding.

2. Background
APRA CPS 234 requires regulated entities to maintain information security capability commensurate with threats, including:

Governance

Incident response

Testing of controls

Third‑party management

Timely breach notification

The vendor provides machine‑learning analytics used to detect anomalous transactions.
Because the vendor processes sensitive financial data, CPS 234 applies directly.

Your role:

Conduct a CPS 234‑aligned readiness assessment

Identify gaps

Evaluate operational and regulatory risk

Recommend remediation steps

3. Scope
This assessment covers:

Information security governance

Incident response capability

Control testing

Third‑party dependency management

Breach notification

Data protection and access control

4. Assessment Methodology
Reviewed vendor policies, SOC 2 report, and architecture diagrams

Conducted interviews with CTO and security lead

Evaluated cloud environment configuration

Mapped findings to CPS 234 requirements

Assessed risk severity and likelihood

5. Findings (Mapped to APRA CPS 234 Requirements)
Finding 1 — Insufficient Information Security Capability
CPS 234 Requirement:  
Regulated entities must ensure third parties maintain security capability commensurate with threats.

Issue:  
Vendor has no dedicated security team; security responsibilities distributed informally across engineering.

Risk:  
Slow response to threats; unclear accountability.

Severity: High
Likelihood: Medium

Finding 2 — No Evidence of Control Effectiveness Testing
CPS 234 Requirement:  
Controls must be regularly tested for effectiveness.

Issue:  
Vendor has never conducted:

Penetration testing

Vulnerability scanning

Incident simulation exercises

Risk:  
Unknown vulnerabilities; untested response capability.

Severity: High
Likelihood: High

Finding 3 — Weak Third‑Party Dependency Management
CPS 234 Requirement:  
Entities must assess security capability of third‑party suppliers.

Issue:  
Vendor relies on multiple sub‑processors but has no formal vendor‑risk program.

Risk:  
Cascading supply‑chain vulnerabilities.

Severity: Medium
Likelihood: High

Finding 4 — No Formal Incident Response Testing
CPS 234 Requirement:  
Entities must test incident response plans regularly.

Issue:  
Vendor has an IR plan but has never conducted a tabletop or simulation.

Risk:  
Unprepared for real‑world breach scenarios.

Severity: High
Likelihood: Medium

Finding 5 — Breach Notification Not Timely
CPS 234 Requirement:  
Entities must notify APRA within 72 hours of material incidents.

Issue:  
Vendor’s policy states 7‑day notification window.

Risk:  
Regulatory non‑compliance for the bank.

Severity: High
Likelihood: Medium

Finding 6 — Incomplete Access Control Governance
CPS 234 Requirement:  
Access must be restricted to authorized personnel only.

Issue:

No quarterly access reviews

No MFA for privileged accounts

No logging of administrative actions

Risk:  
Unauthorized access to financial data.

Severity: High
Likelihood: High

6. Human Behavior Analysis (Psychology Lens)
Start‑Up Bias
Vendor leadership prioritizes speed and innovation over security maturity.

Optimism Bias
Assumption that “we’re too small to be targeted.”

Informal Culture Drift
Security responsibilities are “everyone’s job,” which means they are no one’s job.

Cognitive Overload
Engineers overwhelmed by dual responsibilities (development + security).

7. Recommendations
Governance
Establish dedicated security function

Implement formal vendor‑risk management

Align breach notification timelines with CPS 234

Technical
Enforce MFA for all privileged accounts

Implement quarterly access reviews

Enable logging and monitoring for admin actions

Conduct annual penetration testing

Operational
Conduct incident response tabletop exercises

Document sub‑processor dependencies

Implement continuous vulnerability scanning

